SIMPLE: pursuivant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pursuivant
<hw>Pur"sui*vant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>poursuivant</ets>, fr. <ets>poursuivre</ets>. See <er>Pursue</er>,
and cf. <er>Pursuant</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>poursuivant</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Heralds'
College)</fld> <def>A functionary of lower rank than a herald, but
discharging similar duties; -- called also <altname>pursuivant at
arms</altname>; an attendant of the heralds. Also used
figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The herald Hope, forerunning Fear,⟦br⟧
And Fear, the <qex>pursuivant</qex> of Hope.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The king's messenger; a state messenger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One <qex>pursuivant</qex> who attempted to execute a warrant there
was murdered.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pursuivant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pursuivant
<hw>Pur"sui*vant</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To pursue.</def>
<mark>[Obs. & R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their navy was <qex>pursuivanted</qex> after with a horrible
tempest.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pursy</ent>⟦br⟧
